		<div id="comment_body_64608159"><p>&gt; modprobe, lsmod, and rmmod disagree with you.</p><p>Linux is still a monolith even though it supports dynamic linking.</p><p>The reason is that it doesn't have a stable API and even less of a stable ABI. To write a module, you have to compile it with the current kernel header files, even a minor change in the kernel will break your modules, that's why DKMS is a thing. And even with that, the kernel devs may at some point decide to break the API you are relying on, without warning. The way you are supposed to have li<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
