	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64606433">I could be wrong, but today's world seems a lot more like the mainframe world of the 80s than the freedom days of the late 90s and early 2000s. My phone computer is near useless if I don't have a lot of subscriptions for every app I use and if I don't pay the basic data rate either, and when the servers go down it's time to go have a beer somewhere. My laptop spies on me, and already tells me what I ought to search for on the web instead of what I actually typed in. Soon it will copilot my keyboard, expect to write my letters for me (for a small price) and make spreadsheets for me (for a small price) and control video conferencing (for a small price). And if the work wifi goes down, the AI becomes too dumb to speak and it's time to go have a beer somewhere. My FOSS applications are written or maintained by employees of large tech companies sitting in a cathedral on campus, who only solve problems if it makes sense for themselves. Overall, it feels like there's a lot of stuff available for free, but somehow I still have to pay a lot for all this freedom and if I try to step outside the guardrails, somehow that's not supported and crickets.</div>
	</div>

